<font color="#FF0000">LESSONS LEARNED MEMORIES FOUND</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 11 17:49:55 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Dear Doc Del<br><br>
What outstanding resources you must have.<br><br>
My diary (a spiral notebook) was always kept with our gear usually on Hill 65 or at Liberty Bridge. The area of our responsibility was in the Dai Loc area, Hill 55, 37, 10, 41, 52, Dodge City, Arizona Territory, Sung Thu Bon and Via Gia Rivers. <br><br>
I entered information only after the operations and when I returned stateside rewrote much of it  while most things were still fresh in my mind (I still have the original notebook, minus the cover)  All of it just sat there for 30 years until recently when I picked it up again and began to edit and rewrite the diary into  bookform for publication.<br><br>
The original diary entry shows that we were operating in an area called Independence, where we had fought operation Foster in. It was also known as Arizona Territory and was located between the Song Thu Bon River to the North and the Via Gia on the south side near An Hoa. <br><br>
The original entry for March reads:<br><br>
&quot;7th      James spotted gooks in rice paddie and tree line. Williams was gone so I had to man the gun again.<br><br>
8th       early dawn and NVA still in the area.<br><br>
9th       moved up in Arizona Territory, set up (that night) with gooks sitting on bank on top of us (it was so dark we had set up our ambush facing an embankment). <br>
Got caught out in the open at night by myself (when the enemy opened up on us, we were out gunned and we withdrew, I became separated from my unit and had to crawl back all night until I found them on a little hill). <br><br>
10th       ran into Army, moving around Foster area as if nothing could happen. Got choppered out and went into battalion (3/7) (we then became reactionary force while 1/7 was out on operation &quot;Worth&quot;).<br><br>
(Items in brackets I added -here- for clarification) <br><br>
I am trying keeping it as factual as possible and what is interesting is that of the 47 Marines in 1st platoon 28 of which I have been able to make contact with, we all remember certain aspects of our tour and in the compilation of their memories with the dates and after action reports things are pretty accurate as to what transpired. I may have some info off a bit, but it is pretty much coming together. <br>
Once the book is published I hope that it will reflect history as it occurred reflecting our time, era and experiences.<br><br>
One thing I learned about our Vietnam memories is that most of those that I have contacted have not added to their stories of the incidents or facts.  Most chooose to remain silent and have not shared their experiences with hardly anyone. I also have learned that most have downplayed their individual contributions to the overall security or to the protection of the unit. Most view their time and contribution as worthwhile, solemn, reflective and honorable.  I have found very few incidents where someone did things that they would not want included in the book. <br><br>
 Of the 28 in our platoon I have had contact with all have lead productive lives and only two of the three who had been captured and stripped of the clothes and weapons by the NVA have any lingering problems associated with their tour of duty.<br><br>
Thanks for the info. <br><br>

<p><code>--   Cookbarela@iname.com  (cook Barela) </code><p>


